        // ── AI Help & Smart Search (Article) ─────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "AI Help & Smart Search",
            Slug = "ai-help-and-search",
            Summary = "The two AI surfaces that live in the global header on every page: the AI Help panel (a persistent, streaming chat that suggests related training) and the AI column in global search (RAG answers and result chunks that jump to records).",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/dashboard"]""",
            Tags = """["ai","help","search","header","rag"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## AI Help & Smart Search\n\nBeyond the dedicated AI page (/ai), there are two AI surfaces built into the global header that follow you on every page. They are different from the /ai assistants and behave differently — this module covers both.\n\n### 1. The AI Help Panel\n\nClick the **robot icon** (smart_toy) in the header's action row to open the AI Help panel — a slide-out chat on the right side of the screen. This is your in-app help assistant: ask it how to do something in Forge and it answers in plain language. The panel only appears when AI is available for your install (the icon is hidden when the AI capability is off or the AI service is down).\n\n**Welcome screen and starters.** When the panel is empty it shows a welcome message and four starter buttons — 'How do I create a new job?', 'How does the quote to order workflow work?', 'How do I track inventory?', and 'What keyboard shortcuts are available?'. Click any starter to send it, or type your own question in the input at the bottom and press Enter.\n\n**Streaming answers.** Answers stream in token-by-token, so you see the response build in real time (a blinking cursor marks the streaming position). Assistant replies are rendered as formatted Markdown — headings, lists, bold, and code all display properly.\n\n**Related training links.** After an answer finishes, the panel may show a 'Related training:' section with up to three module links chosen based on the page you are currently on. Click one to open that training module — the panel passes your current route so the suggestions are relevant to where you are working.\n\n**Conversations persist.** Unlike the /ai page (which keeps chats only in memory), the AI Help panel saves your conversation to your browser's local storage under a per-user key. Your chat survives a page refresh, closing the tab, and reopening later — and it syncs across browser tabs, so the same conversation appears everywhere you have Forge open. The history is capped at the most recent 50 messages.\n\n**Clearing.** Click the **restart_alt** icon in the panel header to start a fresh conversation. This clears the stored history. Click the **close** (X) icon, the backdrop, or the robot icon again to hide the panel without clearing anything.\n\n### 2. The AI Column in Global Search\n\nThe header search box (press **Ctrl+K** to focus it) is a normal entity search — type and it finds jobs, parts, customers, and other records by keyword. When AI is available, the results dropdown splits into **two columns**:\n\n- **Left column — Results:** the standard keyword matches. Click one to navigate to that record.\n- **Right column — AI Results:** an AI-powered (RAG) view of the same query. While the AI is working you'll see an 'auto_awesome' spinner and a 'Thinking…' label.\n\n**The AI answer.** At the top of the AI column, the assistant may show a short generated **answer** (with a lightbulb icon) — a direct, plain-language response synthesized from your indexed data.\n\n**AI result chunks.** Below the answer is a list of semantically matched chunks. Each chunk shows the matched text, the entity type, the source field it came from, and a relevance **score** as a percentage. Click any AI result to **navigate straight to that record** — the AI column is not just informational, it's a way to find and open records that a keyword search might miss.\n\n### When to Use Which\n\n- **Use the AI Help panel** when you have a 'how do I…' or 'what does this do' question about Forge itself — process, workflow, where-to-click, keyboard shortcuts.\n- **Use AI search** when you're looking for a specific record but only remember a description or detail, not the exact number — the RAG column surfaces matches by meaning, not just exact text, and lets you jump right to the record.\n\n### Availability\n\nBoth surfaces depend on the AI service being reachable and the AI capability being enabled for your install. If AI is turned off or the AI container is down, the robot icon disappears from the header and the search dropdown shows only the standard Results column — the rest of Forge works exactly as before.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── AI Drafting & Summarizing (QuickRef) ─────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "AI Drafting & Summarizing",
            Slug = "ai-drafting-summarizing",
            Summary = "Reference for the AI generate (drafting) and summarize affordances: what they do, where they appear, what they send, and how they behave when AI is unavailable.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.QuickRef,
            EstimatedMinutes = 3,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 6,
            AppRoutes = """["/ai"]""",
            Tags = """["ai","drafting","summarize","reference"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"title":"AI Drafting & Summarizing","groups":[{"heading":"What These Do","items":[{"label":"Drafting (generate)","value":"Produces new text from a prompt you provide — for example drafting a job description, a customer email, a part description, or documentation. You give it an instruction; it returns written content you can edit and use."},{"label":"Summarizing (summarize)","value":"Condenses a block of existing text into a short summary — for example boiling a long note, description, or thread down to its key points."},{"label":"Relationship to chat","value":"Drafting and summarizing are one-shot text operations, not a back-and-forth conversation. Unlike the AI Help panel or an /ai assistant, there is no message history — each call stands alone."}]},{"heading":"How They Behave","items":[{"label":"Single request, single response","value":"Each draft or summary is one request and one returned block of text. There is no streaming cursor and no follow-up turns — you get the full result at once."},{"label":"Output is editable","value":"AI output is a starting point, never a final commit. Review and edit the generated text before saving it onto a record. The AI does not write to your data on its own."},{"label":"Grounding","value":"Drafting works from the prompt you give it. Summarizing works from the text you hand it. Neither pulls from your indexed records the way RAG search does — what you provide is what it works with."}]},{"heading":"Availability & Limits","items":[{"label":"Capability gated","value":"Both require the AI capability to be enabled for your install (CAP-EXT-AI-ASSISTANT) and the AI service to be reachable. When AI is off or the container is down, drafting and summarizing affordances are hidden or disabled — the underlying screen still works without them."},{"label":"Graceful degradation","value":"If a draft or summarize request fails, the feature degrades quietly: you keep whatever you had, and no partial or broken text is written to a record."},{"label":"Backed by the same engine","value":"Drafting and summarizing use the same self-hosted AI engine as the rest of the AI features (generate and summarize endpoints on the AI service). No data leaves your install to a third-party AI provider."}]},{"heading":"Good Use Cases","items":[{"label":"First-draft writing","value":"Job descriptions, customer-facing emails, part or process descriptions, internal documentation — anywhere a blank page is the hard part."},{"label":"Condensing","value":"Turning a long note, inspection comment, or description into a one- or two-line summary for a header or report."},{"label":"Not a system of record","value":"Do not treat AI output as authoritative data. It is a writing aid — a human reviews and owns the final text."}]}]}"""
        });

