            AppRoutes = """["/ai"]""",
            Tags = """["ai","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Temperature & Max Context Chunks tuning\n\nEvery assistant carries two advanced model-tuning fields, exposed under **Advanced Settings** in the assistant editor (Admin → AI Assistants).\n\n- **Temperature** (`Temperature`, default **0.7**, range 0–1) — controls answer creativity/randomness. Lower (toward 0) makes answers more deterministic and conservative; higher (toward 1) makes them more varied. Leave at the default unless an assistant needs tighter, more repeatable output.\n- **Max Context Chunks** (`MaxContextChunks`, default **5**, range 1–20) — how many retrieved RAG chunks the assistant pulls into its context when answering. More chunks = more grounding data but a longer, slower prompt; fewer = faster but narrower. The default of 5 is a balanced starting point.\n\nBoth are per-assistant, not global — a focused HR assistant and a broad general assistant can be tuned independently. They do not change the model itself, only how it is prompted.\n\n## Built-in vs custom assistants & deletion rules\n\nAssistants are either **built-in** (seeded by the system, `IsBuiltIn = true`, shown with a 'Built In' chip in the admin list) or **custom** (created by an admin).\n\n- **Built-in assistants can be edited but NOT deleted.** A delete on a built-in returns a 409 with the message 'Built-in assistants cannot be deleted. Disable them instead.' To retire one, turn off its **Active** toggle — it disappears from the `/ai` page for users while remaining configured.\n- **Custom assistants can be deleted.** Deletion is a soft delete (`DeletedAt` stamped), consistent with the rest of Forge — the row is hidden, not physically removed.\n- The **General** category is special: the `/ai` page resolves its 'general' route to whichever assistant has `Category = General`. Keep one General assistant active so that route always lands somewhere.\n\n## Capability gating & container-down degradation\n\nAll AI surfaces sit behind one capability: **CAP-EXT-AI-ASSISTANT**. Both `AiController` and `AiAssistantsController` carry `[RequiresCapability(\"CAP-EXT-AI-ASSISTANT\")]`, so when the capability is disabled for an install every AI endpoint short-circuits with a 403 capability envelope.\n\n- **Capability off:** the header robot (smart_toy) icon is hidden, the global-search AI column does not render, and the `/ai` page / drafting / summarizing affordances are unavailable. The rest of Forge is unaffected.\n- **Container down (capability on, service unreachable):** the AI is self-hosted (Ollama + pgvector). If the AI container is down, AI features **degrade gracefully** rather than erroring the page — search falls back to the standard keyword-only Results column, and chat/draft/summarize requests fail quietly without writing partial data. No third-party AI provider is ever called; nothing leaves the install.\n\n## RAG document indexing\n\nAssistant grounding and the global-search AI column are powered by a RAG index, not by live database scans.\n\n- Indexed content lives in the **DocumentEmbedding** entity — a pgvector `vector(384)` column. Records are chunked and embedded so they can be matched semantically.\n- Endpoints on `AiController`: `POST /api/v1/ai/index` (index one entity — body `{entityType, entityId}`, returns `chunksIndexed`), `POST /api/v1/ai/bulk-index` (index many, returns `totalChunksIndexed`), and `POST /api/v1/ai/search` (RagSearch).\n- A Hangfire job, **DocumentIndexJob**, re-indexes on a schedule (about every 30 minutes), so newly created/edited records become searchable without a manual index call.\n- An assistant's **Allowed Entity Types** (`AllowedEntityTypes`, default `[]` = all) scopes which indexed entity types it may draw on — this is how RAG grounding is kept in an assistant's lane (e.g. an HR assistant limited to employee data). Empty means all types are fair game.\n\n## Help panel: cross-tab sync & 50-message cap\n\nThe global-header AI Help panel persists differently from the `/ai` page (which is in-memory only).\n\n- **Per-user local storage.** History is saved to `localStorage` under the key `ai-help:{userId}` (or `ai-help:anon` when no user). It survives refresh, tab close, and reopen.\n- **Cross-tab sync.** The panel listens for the browser `storage` event on that key, so sending a message in one tab updates the conversation in every other open Forge tab for the same user — a single shared conversation across tabs.\n- **50-message cap.** Stored history is capped at the most recent **50** messages (`MAX_STORED_MESSAGES = 50`); each save slices to the last 50. Older messages roll off.\n- **Clearing** removes the stored key (`restart_alt` icon). If `localStorage` is full, a save is skipped silently rather than throwing — the conversation still works in-session, it just may not persist that turn.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded AI Assistant training modules");
    }
